title: Regan Smith wins NASCAR Xfinity Series race in Delaware
text:
Regan Smith wins NASCAR Xfinity Series race in Delaware Originally published October 3, 2015 at 7:19 pm Driver Regan Smith strengthened his championship push in NASCAR’s second-tier series with a victory in the Hisense 200 at Dover International Speedway. The Associated Press 
DOVER, Del. – Regan Smith might leave JR Motorsports with one heck of a parting gift. 
Smith wants to stay with his Xfinity Series team next year. But if he has to go, he would gladly take a championship trophy with him. 
Smith strengthened his championship push in NASCAR’s second-tier series with a victory Saturday in the Hisense 200 at Dover International Speedway. 
“I’m trying to figure some things out for next year, so wins never hurt,” Smith said. “That’s never a bad thing going forward.” Most Read Stories Unlimited Digital Access. $1 for 4 weeks. 
Smith, 32, won for the second time this year and is 36 points behind series leader Chris Buescher with five races to go. 
Smith would like to add a championship to his résumé. He faces an uncertain future with JR Motorsports after the organization signed Elliott Sadler for next season. JRM also fields a car for defending series champion Chase Elliott and has a multi-driver car. 
JR Motorsports is the race team for NASCAR superstar driver Dale Earnhardt Jr., who stopped by the media center to congratulate Smith. 
But Smith’s future employment was a worry for another day — he was headed out to pound some beers. 
“I’m going to have a headache tomorrow, I’m not going to lie,” Smith said. 
Denny Hamlin was second, ahead of Joe Gibbs Racing teammate Kyle Busch. Ryan Blaney was fourth and Kyle Larson finished fifth. 
“You can’t pass here. You know there’s no outside groove to get going on anything,” Busch said. 
Buescher finished eighth and is 24 points ahead of second-place Elliott. 
“There’s plenty of racing left and this thing is far from over,” Buescher said. “If we just go out and run our race and try not to worry too much about the points, we should be in good shape.” 
Derrike Cope of Spanaway finished 32nd of 40. Seattle Times staff
